  { question: "How do you calculate profit on a call option?", answer: "For a long call option, profit per share equals the underlying price minus the strike price minus the premium paid. Total profit is profit per share multiplied by the number of shares (contracts times 100). If the underlying price is below the strike price, you lose the premium paid. Your break-even point is the strike price plus the premium." },
  { question: "How do you calculate profit on a put option?", answer: "For a long put option, profit per share equals the strike price minus the underlying price minus the premium paid. Total profit is profit per share multiplied by the number of shares (contracts times 100). If the underlying price is above the strike price, you lose the premium paid. Your break-even point is the strike price minus the premium." },
  { question: "What is the maximum loss when buying options?", answer: "When buying options (calls or puts), your maximum loss is limited to the total premium paid, which equals the premium per share times 100 shares per contract times the number of contracts. This defined risk is one of the key advantages of buying options versus selling them." },
  { question: "What does it mean when an option is in the money?", answer: "A call option is in the money when the underlying price is above the strike price. A put option is in the money when the underlying price is below the strike price. In-the-money options have intrinsic value, meaning they would be worth exercising at expiration." },
  { question: "How is the break-even price calculated for options?", answer: "For a call option, break-even equals the strike price plus the premium paid. For a put option, break-even equals the strike price minus the premium paid. At the break-even price, you recover your entire premium with no profit or loss." }
